      • hasNextSoft

        public Pullable.NextStatus hasNextSoft()
        Description copied from interface: Pullable
        Determines if an event can be pulled from the output. Depending on what happens, the possible return values are:
        • If one of the inputs answers "no" when called for Pullable.hasNextSoft(), returns "no"
        • If one of the inputs answers "maybe" when called for Pullable.hasNextSoft(), returns "maybe"
        • If all inputs answer "yes" when called for Pullable.hasNextSoft(), but no event is produced with the given inputs, returns "maybe"
        • Otherwise, returns "yes"
        Therefore, the method is lazy in that it asks events from its input only once, and attempts to produce an output event only once.
        Specified by:
        hasNextSoft in interface Pullable
        Returns:
        Whether a next event exists

      • hasNext

        public boolean hasNext()
        Description copied from interface: Pullable
        Determines if an event can be pulled from the output, by trying "harder" than Pullable.hasNextSoft(). Depending on what happens, the possible return values are:
        • If one of the inputs answers "no" when called for Pullable.hasNextSoft(), returns "no"
        • If all inputs answer "yes" when called for Pullable.hasNextSoft(), and an event is produced with the given inputs, returns "yes"
        • Otherwise, the method will keep calling #hasNextHard on the inputs as long as they don't answer "no", and will try to produce an output event until one is produced.
        • To avoid infinite looping, the method eventually gives up (and answers "no") after some maximum number of repetitions is reached. This is configured by the static field Pullable.s_maxRetries.
        Specified by:
        hasNext in interface Pullable
        Specified by:
        hasNext in interface Iterator<Object>
        Returns:
        Whether a next event exists

      • dispose

        public void dispose()
        Description copied from interface: Pullable
        Tells this pullable that methods Pullable.pull(), Pullable.pullSoft(), Pullable.hasNext() and Pullable.hasNextSoft() will not be called anymore. For some types of pullables, this can be used as a cue to free some resources (such as threads). The behaviour of these four methods after dispose() has been called is undefined. In future versions, it is possible that an exception will be thrown in such a case.
        Specified by:
        dispose in interface Pullable
